commits.message:
TypeScript 4.9

Upgrade to use TypeScript 4.9.

Convert fusionjs to TypeScript

- converted most the codebase to typescript using [flowts](https://github.com/zxbodya/flowts) (which I am building).
- did manual fixes to make type check passing (proper fixes for important parts like `fusion-core` or where it was easy, `ts-ignore` for things that are not immediately clear to reduce the number of changes needed)

commits are organized in a few groups:
1. updates in fusionjs (eslint support for typescript, new prettier, etc.)
2. backport some type improvements (basically fixing some incorrect/missing types which flow happen to ignore)
3. updates in configuration/dependencies needed to have typescript
4. `flowts: rename / convert` - automated part, done in two commits to better preserve sources history (this part does not really need to be reviewed, because as part of migration it is verified to be exactly the same ast after removing type information)
5. manual fixes

remaining part/next steps:

1. to align plans on this with the team (please comment if you have ideas/suggestions to move this forward )
2. maybe to land some parts of this before the whole thing? (prettier, eslint basic ts support, backported type improvements…)
3. update build scripts (https://github.com/rtsao/create-universal-package/pull/47) and test configuration
4. can be separate, but before publishing ts type definitions, it would make sense to first update `fusion-cli` babel config to allow actually running fusionjs project using typescript
6. cleanup - there are some helper scripts I created to automate more things, and when everything is done - they to be removed

aside complete migration to typescript(which is the ideal end goal), this can be already useful to improve some things gradually:

 - to generate `d.ts` files, to be published with - and so significantly to improve typescript experience with fusion
 - there is a way to use `d.ts` files to generate flow definition files, reducing the amount of manual work needed to do so (this can be helpful to improve flow performance in existing projects)

compiling it with typescript:

- added `private/everything` and `public/everything` - basically, it is a packages depending on everything else, so it is possible to have all dependencies at once to type check on the whole project at once
- to do it in an individual package - use `tsc -b .` (and with `--force` when suspecting something wrong with build cache)

Also, this is to be useful to evaluate how nicely TypeScript works in monorepo ❤️

commits.message:
Upgrade all projects to Jest 28.1.3

Upgrades Jest to 28.1.3 from the old 25.x version that was used prior.

Bulk of changes were because of Jest not allowing `async` and `done` to be used in the same test. So most were converted to drop the `async` and instead use promises instead while retaining the usage of `done`. In these cases, these tests still work because jest will wait for the allotted test time (default 5 seconds) for `done` to be called, allowing the test enough time to do its async behavior and assertions. If after that time `done` hasn't been called due to assertion failure or the test throwing, the test will fail.

There were a good number of tests that are `async` and also defined a done callback that didn't need it so I just removed the done callback.

There were a few changes of more importance:

1. [`jest-resolver-fusion-browser`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-f281dca345b410750bc0fa0c1a758fadc8d741895a588d64f574ba01ed9b294a) was added for the few projects that needed this resolver in order for tests to work. The old solution was to have one shared package between server and browser but Jest removed support for reading the `browser: true` field in the jest configuration. So there wasn't an elegant way to share the custom resolver anymore and thus it had to split as a separate one.
2. [`fusion-core`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-1d88b1de126f4a188756f3f0df97f912a4d4097aaaa2a9644cf2f53673cba512) required brand new snapshots since the old ones that defined the error stack available from tokens was changed. None of the code changed though so I chalked it up to Jest implementation details that resulted in changed snapshots.
3. [`fusion-plugin-error-handling`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-7ce50697fec9acb0a77a870fb18300b53992e3de4deff5e26d73af67b1614260) was doing some Proxy magic that got bit by some new Jest function calls that happened on load. That was a pain to figure out and fix.
4. Some tests needed additional timeouts defined as the old ones were too short now.

commits.message:
TypeScript 4.9

Upgrade to use TypeScript 4.9.

Convert fusionjs to TypeScript

- converted most the codebase to typescript using [flowts](https://github.com/zxbodya/flowts) (which I am building).
- did manual fixes to make type check passing (proper fixes for important parts like `fusion-core` or where it was easy, `ts-ignore` for things that are not immediately clear to reduce the number of changes needed)

commits are organized in a few groups:
1. updates in fusionjs (eslint support for typescript, new prettier, etc.)
2. backport some type improvements (basically fixing some incorrect/missing types which flow happen to ignore)
3. updates in configuration/dependencies needed to have typescript
4. `flowts: rename / convert` - automated part, done in two commits to better preserve sources history (this part does not really need to be reviewed, because as part of migration it is verified to be exactly the same ast after removing type information)
5. manual fixes

remaining part/next steps:

1. to align plans on this with the team (please comment if you have ideas/suggestions to move this forward )
2. maybe to land some parts of this before the whole thing? (prettier, eslint basic ts support, backported type improvements…)
3. update build scripts (https://github.com/rtsao/create-universal-package/pull/47) and test configuration
4. can be separate, but before publishing ts type definitions, it would make sense to first update `fusion-cli` babel config to allow actually running fusionjs project using typescript
6. cleanup - there are some helper scripts I created to automate more things, and when everything is done - they to be removed

aside complete migration to typescript(which is the ideal end goal), this can be already useful to improve some things gradually:

 - to generate `d.ts` files, to be published with - and so significantly to improve typescript experience with fusion
 - there is a way to use `d.ts` files to generate flow definition files, reducing the amount of manual work needed to do so (this can be helpful to improve flow performance in existing projects)

compiling it with typescript:

- added `private/everything` and `public/everything` - basically, it is a packages depending on everything else, so it is possible to have all dependencies at once to type check on the whole project at once
- to do it in an individual package - use `tsc -b .` (and with `--force` when suspecting something wrong with build cache)

Also, this is to be useful to evaluate how nicely TypeScript works in monorepo ❤️

commits.message:
Upgrade all projects to Jest 28.1.3

Upgrades Jest to 28.1.3 from the old 25.x version that was used prior.

Bulk of changes were because of Jest not allowing `async` and `done` to be used in the same test. So most were converted to drop the `async` and instead use promises instead while retaining the usage of `done`. In these cases, these tests still work because jest will wait for the allotted test time (default 5 seconds) for `done` to be called, allowing the test enough time to do its async behavior and assertions. If after that time `done` hasn't been called due to assertion failure or the test throwing, the test will fail.

There were a good number of tests that are `async` and also defined a done callback that didn't need it so I just removed the done callback.

There were a few changes of more importance:

1. [`jest-resolver-fusion-browser`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-f281dca345b410750bc0fa0c1a758fadc8d741895a588d64f574ba01ed9b294a) was added for the few projects that needed this resolver in order for tests to work. The old solution was to have one shared package between server and browser but Jest removed support for reading the `browser: true` field in the jest configuration. So there wasn't an elegant way to share the custom resolver anymore and thus it had to split as a separate one.
2. [`fusion-core`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-1d88b1de126f4a188756f3f0df97f912a4d4097aaaa2a9644cf2f53673cba512) required brand new snapshots since the old ones that defined the error stack available from tokens was changed. None of the code changed though so I chalked it up to Jest implementation details that resulted in changed snapshots.
3. [`fusion-plugin-error-handling`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-7ce50697fec9acb0a77a870fb18300b53992e3de4deff5e26d73af67b1614260) was doing some Proxy magic that got bit by some new Jest function calls that happened on load. That was a pain to figure out and fix.
4. Some tests needed additional timeouts defined as the old ones were too short now.

commits.message:
TypeScript 4.9

Upgrade to use TypeScript 4.9.

Convert fusionjs to TypeScript

- converted most the codebase to typescript using [flowts](https://github.com/zxbodya/flowts) (which I am building).
- did manual fixes to make type check passing (proper fixes for important parts like `fusion-core` or where it was easy, `ts-ignore` for things that are not immediately clear to reduce the number of changes needed)

commits are organized in a few groups:
1. updates in fusionjs (eslint support for typescript, new prettier, etc.)
2. backport some type improvements (basically fixing some incorrect/missing types which flow happen to ignore)
3. updates in configuration/dependencies needed to have typescript
4. `flowts: rename / convert` - automated part, done in two commits to better preserve sources history (this part does not really need to be reviewed, because as part of migration it is verified to be exactly the same ast after removing type information)
5. manual fixes

remaining part/next steps:

1. to align plans on this with the team (please comment if you have ideas/suggestions to move this forward )
2. maybe to land some parts of this before the whole thing? (prettier, eslint basic ts support, backported type improvements…)
3. update build scripts (https://github.com/rtsao/create-universal-package/pull/47) and test configuration
4. can be separate, but before publishing ts type definitions, it would make sense to first update `fusion-cli` babel config to allow actually running fusionjs project using typescript
6. cleanup - there are some helper scripts I created to automate more things, and when everything is done - they to be removed

aside complete migration to typescript(which is the ideal end goal), this can be already useful to improve some things gradually:

 - to generate `d.ts` files, to be published with - and so significantly to improve typescript experience with fusion
 - there is a way to use `d.ts` files to generate flow definition files, reducing the amount of manual work needed to do so (this can be helpful to improve flow performance in existing projects)

compiling it with typescript:

- added `private/everything` and `public/everything` - basically, it is a packages depending on everything else, so it is possible to have all dependencies at once to type check on the whole project at once
- to do it in an individual package - use `tsc -b .` (and with `--force` when suspecting something wrong with build cache)

Also, this is to be useful to evaluate how nicely TypeScript works in monorepo ❤️

commits.message:
Upgrade all projects to Jest 28.1.3

Upgrades Jest to 28.1.3 from the old 25.x version that was used prior.

Bulk of changes were because of Jest not allowing `async` and `done` to be used in the same test. So most were converted to drop the `async` and instead use promises instead while retaining the usage of `done`. In these cases, these tests still work because jest will wait for the allotted test time (default 5 seconds) for `done` to be called, allowing the test enough time to do its async behavior and assertions. If after that time `done` hasn't been called due to assertion failure or the test throwing, the test will fail.

There were a good number of tests that are `async` and also defined a done callback that didn't need it so I just removed the done callback.

There were a few changes of more importance:

1. [`jest-resolver-fusion-browser`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-f281dca345b410750bc0fa0c1a758fadc8d741895a588d64f574ba01ed9b294a) was added for the few projects that needed this resolver in order for tests to work. The old solution was to have one shared package between server and browser but Jest removed support for reading the `browser: true` field in the jest configuration. So there wasn't an elegant way to share the custom resolver anymore and thus it had to split as a separate one.
2. [`fusion-core`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-1d88b1de126f4a188756f3f0df97f912a4d4097aaaa2a9644cf2f53673cba512) required brand new snapshots since the old ones that defined the error stack available from tokens was changed. None of the code changed though so I chalked it up to Jest implementation details that resulted in changed snapshots.
3. [`fusion-plugin-error-handling`](https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1530/files#diff-7ce50697fec9acb0a77a870fb18300b53992e3de4deff5e26d73af67b1614260) was doing some Proxy magic that got bit by some new Jest function calls that happened on load. That was a pain to figure out and fix.
4. Some tests needed additional timeouts defined as the old ones were too short now.

Adding yarn.lock to git ignore to support the import command, which may fail to apply patches if the file does not exist in the upstream repository.

Fix React Router history bug where basename is not applied to initial server render

In the React Router 5 implementation, when the server history object was created, the prefix was prepended to the current URL: https://github.com/uber/fusionjs/pull/1409/files#diff-b9d2e3755ea5d8daffc083230c68bfcea742135f9fca8a8aa7f54d13467c6017L103

This behavior was incorrectly removed in the RR6 implementation. The history location should always have the basename/prefix as part of the URL since that's what React Router expects.

Also include a small fix to fusion-plugin-apollo where if we are in dev mode, to log out SSR errors the way we do in fusion-react. This is so the errors show up in dev.

Add onRecoverableError handler to hydrateRoot

Instead of throwing an uncaught error on hydration mismatches in React 18, capture the uncaught using the `onRecoverableError` handler and re-fire it as a warning instead.
